Russian Communism Rises Again
Moscow - it was many years ago, during my sabbatical from teaching at an American university, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination is not some kind of bastion of free speech.
But there is still some freedom left here.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once toured the country in a bid to win the support of politicians who were not controlled by the Kremlin.
Public protest activities broke out.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts may not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
But the Communist Party is generally regarded as a historical legacy.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, as has the protest movement he launched.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved for "extremism," and its members are facing exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media institutions, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the list of "foreign agents" — even worse — listed as "undesirables."
Over the past year, Russia has slipped into a non-free status, though not far off, it has been quite intense.
For example, the Law on Designating Foreign Agents, which was enacted in 2012, aims to destroy or discredit institutions or individuals who engage in "political activities" and simultaneously receive funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, and it has also been used as a reason to label someone a foreign agent for sharing a tweet.
(The "outcast" label will completely ostracize you.)
Only in this year, a record-breaking 101 new physical entities have been added to the list of foreign agents.
A total of 359 cases includes 88 media-related institutions and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "intermediaries" must be on the list because they "influence national politics."
The core target of news and propaganda work is certainly to influence politics.
The problem lies precisely in this: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself as a future guarantor of control over Russian politics, he perceives criticism as a survival threat.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, it was the Communist Party, an unlikely group, that managed to survive and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This can be largely attributed to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy – that is, urging voters to support those most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed candidates – as the Communist Party showed great strength in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while the United Russia party supported by the Kremlin won nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communist Party refuses to recognize the result, insisting that the voting result has been manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, the Communists seem to be more respected than Putin at the moment.
But they are no longer the original Communists.
They not only did not deny the joys of this world, but party members even wore fur coats, enthusiastically traveled abroad, drove foreign cars, and used social media.
Some people are millionaires – take for instance the charismatic head of the agricultural department Pavel Grudinin, who was barred from participating in last month's election.
Despite being led by 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, the party is increasingly influenced and supported by its young members.
Taking Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
The 36-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed 'Red Navalny', severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform in 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional official suggested that Russians should be able to afford a better life with their monthly salary of around 3,500 rubles, Bondaenko documented his efforts to prove this person wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban on running, Bondarenko still allowed to participate in the national Duma elections held last month.
Despite receiving the support of Navalny's smart voting system, he still lost to the candidate from the United Russia party.
But his potential should not be ignored: he recently drafted a title for a protest, accusing "the state and government of manipulating" United Russia.
Also, there is Anastasia Yudina, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she incredibily lost the last election.
But she was still very popular — — and increasingly — — trendy.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Nagornaya, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
It is ironic that the Communist Party's modernization reform reflects people's nostalgia for the past: In 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality.
In addition, like Navalny of the liberal wing, today's communist party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which a person's wild imagination will not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on such logic that all the opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly joining forces: a "united Russia" formed to counter Putin, within the unified Russia party.
This is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary election in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš, also known as the Czech Donald Trump, failed to continue as prime minister because the opposition coalition put aside their ideological differences and formed a joint coalition, led by its leader Petr Fiala, who may lead a new government together with another opposition coalition.
Just like Fierravanti-Welsh said, "People are fed up with populists," they want "normal, capable and decent politics."
Hungary's opposition will also put up a joint list in next year's parliamentary elections and nominate a joint candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still practises democracy, so Babis is preparing to join the opposition.
While toppling Putin would be much more difficult, it is not hard to predict that there will be more comprehensive measures aimed at smashing the Communist Party.
But such actions also posed a risk to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims "Russian democracy has not died," and points out that there are "vibrant opposition parties" as evidence, which shows that he at least remains interested in pretending that Russia has not been steered towards near-authoritarianism.
Putin stated that all he wants is stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia into even more turbulent circumstances.
If the Kremlin treats the Russian liberal camp with the same capriciousness, formulating and enforcing rules that would drive the Communist Party underground, then social explosion would be even more likely to happen.
But if it decides not to suppress it, the Russian Communists — yes, that is, the Communists — may become a force that cannot be ignored.
